Consistent Hashing via an Example

Let's build up our intuition via a motivating example.
Imagine you're designing a ticketing system like TicketMaster. Initially, your system is simple:
(1) One database storing all event data
(2) Clients making requests to fetch event information
(3) Everything works smoothly at first

But success brings challenges. As your platform grows popular and hosts more events,
a single database can no longer handle the load.
You need to distribute your data across multiple databases – a process called sharding.

The question we need to answer is: How do we know which events to store on which database instance?

First Attempt: Simple Modulo Hashing
The most straightforward approach to distribute data across multiple databases is modulo hashing.
First, we take the event ID and run it through a hash function, which converts it into a number
Then, we take that number and perform the modulo operation (%) with the number of databases
The result tells us which database should store that event

In code, it looks like this:
database_id = hash(event_id) % number_of_databases
For a concrete example with 3 databases:
Event #1234 → hash(1234) % 3 = 1 → Database 1
Event #5678 → hash(5678) % 3 = 0 → Database 0
Event #9012 → hash(9012) % 3 = 2 → Database 2
Great! This works well, until you run into a few problems.
The first problem comes when you want to add a fourth database instance.
To do so, you naively think that all you need to do is run the modulo operation with 4 instead of 3.

database_id = hash(event_id) % 4

You change the code, and push to production but then your database activity goes through the roof!
Not just for the fourth database instance either, but for all of them.
What happened was the change in the hash function did not only impact data that should be stored on the new instance,
but it changed which database instance almost every event was stored on.

Might be prime number can mitigate the issues....

Consist Hashing is the technique that solves the problem of data redistribution when adding or removing a instance in a
distributed system. It is to arrange both data & db in a circular space (hash ring)

(1) hash ring with fixed numbers (2) db nodes on the ring at 0,25,50,75 (3) find the hash value on the ring, move clockwise
until db found.

It's going clockwise, for example new db at 90. only 75-90 need to move. Those events are going to DB1.

If DB2 failed. 0-25 going to DB3.

The problem for the above, when db2 failed and removed. All the events will go to DB3. DB3 now has 2x the load of the
DB1 & 4.

Virtual nodes, we multiple the in the DB hash ring.  Event Mapped to VN(virtual node) will be distributed accordingly
Event will distributed evenly across remaining db instead overlow neighbor only.

Hotspot can still occur, it's when one node gets a disproportionate amount of traffic( A hot event can generate 100 times read)

Consistent hashing doesn't solve the above issue since it's distribute keys only.
(1) Read replicas - replicate popular keys across multiple nodes and load balance can read.(common approach)
(2) Key-space slating: random suffix to hot keys. (redistribution)
(3) Adaptive rebalancing: move key ranges off overloaded nodes. (Internal function in DynamoDB)

In summary:
===========
VN prevents structural imbalance, replication and key salting prevent workload imbalance.

Data Movement in Practice:
==========================
Most distributed db use replication alongside consistent hashing to handle failures.
DynamoDB replicates each partition across three availability zones. Primary node fails, a replica is promoted via
consensus algorithm like Raft.
Cassandra replicating data to N consecutive nodes on the ring.

Data movement happens only at adding capacity or replacing node to restore. Consistent hashing make sue fraction of keys
to be re-replicated.

Consistent Hashing in work
==========================

Consistent hashing not only in db, but anywhere you need to distribute data across cluster or servers.
Like clusters(db/caches/message brokers/set of application servers)

Apache cassandra, hashing to distribute data across the ring.
